    <a href="/reading/probability/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to probability</a>

    <h1>Generating Functions</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Grinstead &amp; Snell &middot; GFDL &middot; <a href="https://math.dartmouth.edu/~prob/prob/prob.pdf">PDF</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Encode a distribution as a polynomial: g(z) = &sum; P(X = k) z&#x1D4F;. Adding independent random variables becomes multiplying their polynomials. Convolution is just polynomial multiplication.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Ordinary generating functions -->
    <h3>Ordinary generating function</h3>
    <p>For a discrete random variable X taking values 0, 1, 2, &hellip;, the <strong>ordinary generating function</strong> (OGF) is g(z) = E[z&#x1D3A;] = &sum;&#x2096; P(X = k) z&#x1D4F;. The coefficients are the probabilities. Evaluating g(1) = 1 (probabilities sum to 1). The derivative g&prime;(1) = E[X].</p>

    <!-- SVG: Polynomial multiplication diagram -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 460 200" class="w-full max-w-lg" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Poly 1: coin flip -->
        <rect x="20" y="30" width="130" height="50" rx="6" fill="#a1a1aa" fill-opacity="0.15" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.2"/>
        <text x="85" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11">g&#x2081;(z) = &frac12; + &frac12;z</text>
        <text x="85" y="68" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.4">coin flip</text>
        <!-- Times sign -->
        <text x="170" y="60" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="18">&times;</text>
        <!-- Poly 2: another coin flip -->
        <rect x="190" y="30" width="130" height="50" rx="6" fill="#a1a1aa" fill-opacity="0.15" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.2"/>
        <text x="255" y="50" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11">g&#x2082;(z) = &frac12; + &frac12;z</text>
        <text x="255" y="68" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.4">coin flip</text>
        <!-- Equals -->
        <text x="340" y="60" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="18">=</text>
        <!-- Product polynomial -->
        <rect x="355" y="25" width="95" height="60" rx="6" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.12" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
        <text x="402" y="48" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="10">&frac14; + &frac12;z + &frac14;z&sup2;</text>
        <text x="402" y="72" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.7">sum of 2 flips</text>
        <!-- Arrow down to coefficients -->
        <line x1="402" y1="90" x2="402" y2="110" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,2"/>
        <!-- Coefficient readout -->
        <text x="230" y="130" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.5">read off coefficients:</text>
        <text x="230" y="150" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11">P(S=0) = &frac14;,  P(S=1) = &frac12;,  P(S=2) = &frac14;</text>
        <!-- Caption -->
        <text x="230" y="185" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="9" fill-opacity="0.35">convolution of distributions = multiplication of polynomials</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Generating functions as polynomial coefficient lists
; g(z) = [p0, p1, p2, ...] means p0 + p1*z + p2*z^2 + ...

; Multiply two polynomials (= convolve two distributions)
(define (poly-mul p q)
  (let* ((m (length p)) (n (length q))
         (result-len (- (+ m n) 1)))
    (let loop ((k 0) (acc '()))
      (if (= k result-len) (reverse acc)
          (let inner ((j 0) (s 0))
            (if (= j m) (loop (+ k 1) (cons s acc))
                (if (and (>= (- k j) 0) (< (- k j) n))
                    (inner (+ j 1) (+ s (* (list-ref p j) (list-ref q (- k j)))))
                    (inner (+ j 1) s))))))))

; Fair coin: P(X=0) = 1/2, P(X=1) = 1/2
(define coin '(0.5 0.5))

; Sum of 2 coins
(define two-coins (poly-mul coin coin))
(display "2 coins: ") (display two-coins) (newline)
; (0.25 0.5 0.25) => P(0)=1/4, P(1)=1/2, P(2)=1/4

; Sum of 3 coins
(define three-coins (poly-mul two-coins coin))
(display "3 coins: ") (display three-coins) (newline)
; (0.125 0.375 0.375 0.125)

; Fair die: P(X=k) = 1/6 for k in 1..6
(define die '(0 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667))
(define two-dice (poly-mul die die))
(display "2 dice:  ") (display two-dice)
; Coefficients give P(sum=2), P(sum=3), ..., P(sum=12)
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import numpy as np

def poly_mul(p, q):
    """Multiply polynomials = convolve distributions."""
    return list(np.convolve(p, q))

coin = [0.5, 0.5]
print("2 coins:", [round(x, 4) for x in poly_mul(coin, coin)])
print("3 coins:", [round(x, 4) for x in poly_mul(poly_mul(coin, coin), coin)])

die = [0] + [1/6]*6
two_dice = poly_mul(die, die)
for s in range(2, 13):
    print(f"  P(sum={s:>2}) = {two_dice[s]:.4f}")
`} />
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Moments from derivatives -->
    <h3>Moments from derivatives</h3>
    <p>The generating function encodes all moments. E[X] = g&prime;(1). E[X(X&minus;1)] = g&Prime;(1), so Var(X) = g&Prime;(1) + g&prime;(1) &minus; (g&prime;(1))&sup2;. No summation needed: just differentiate the polynomial and evaluate at z = 1.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Extract moments from the generating function
; g'(1) = E[X], g''(1) = E[X(X-1)]

; Differentiate a polynomial
(define (poly-deriv p)
  (let loop ((i 1) (acc '()))
    (if (>= i (length p)) (reverse acc)
        (loop (+ i 1) (cons (* i (list-ref p i)) acc)))))

; Evaluate polynomial at z
(define (poly-eval p z)
  (let loop ((i 0) (acc 0) (zk 1))
    (if (>= i (length p)) acc
        (loop (+ i 1) (+ acc (* (list-ref p i) zk)) (* zk z)))))

; Fair die generating function
(define die '(0 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667 0.1667))
(define die-prime (poly-deriv die))
(define die-double (poly-deriv die-prime))

(define mean (poly-eval die-prime 1))
(define factorial-moment (poly-eval die-double 1))
(define variance (+ factorial-moment mean (- (* mean mean))))

(display "E[X] = ") (display mean) (newline)
(display "Var(X) = ") (display variance) (newline)
; E[X] ~ 3.5, Var(X) ~ 2.917
`} />

    <!-- 3. Moment generating functions -->
    <h3>Moment generating function</h3>
    <p>The <strong>moment generating function</strong> (MGF) is M(t) = E[e&#x1D57;&#x1D3A;]. It is the OGF evaluated at z = e&#x1D57;. Its advantage: M&#x2032;(0) = E[X], M&#x2033;(0) = E[X&sup2;], and in general M&#x207D;&#x1D4F;&#x207E;(0) = E[X&#x1D4F;]. The MGF of a sum of independent variables is the product of their MGFs, exactly like the OGF.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Moment generating function: M(t) = E[e^(tX)]
; For a fair die: M(t) = (1/6)(e^t + e^2t + ... + e^6t)

(define (mgf-die t)
  (/ (+ (exp (* 1 t)) (exp (* 2 t)) (exp (* 3 t))
        (exp (* 4 t)) (exp (* 5 t)) (exp (* 6 t)))
     6))

; Numerical derivative to extract moments
(define h 0.0001)
(define (num-deriv f x)
  (/ (- (f (+ x h)) (f (- x h))) (* 2 h)))

(define (num-deriv2 f x)
  (/ (+ (f (+ x h)) (f (- x h)) (* -2 (f x))) (* h h)))

(display "M(0)   = ") (display (mgf-die 0)) (newline)
(display "M'(0)  = E[X]  = ") (display (num-deriv mgf-die 0)) (newline)
(display "M''(0) = E[X^2] = ") (display (num-deriv2 mgf-die 0)) (newline)
(define ex (num-deriv mgf-die 0))
(define ex2 (num-deriv2 mgf-die 0))
(display "Var(X) = E[X^2] - E[X]^2 = ") (display (- ex2 (* ex ex)))
`} />

